    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Spectrum Efficiency Evaluation of Wireless Broadband Networks in The Presence of Co-Channel and Adjacent Channel Interference with Diversity Combining</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Thai Subha.S</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Spectrum Efficiency Evalution<br />Presence of Co-Channel</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Mar-2012 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0054</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">ABSTRACT
The aim of this research work is to investigate theoretical spectral
efficiency limits of adaptive modulation in Rayleigh fading channels. Shannon
capacity of a channel defines its theoretical upper bound for the maximum rate
of data transmission at an arbitrarily small Bit Error Rate, without any delay or
complexity constraints. System performance in the presence of Co-channel and
Adjacent channel interference using various parametric measures, such as
Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF), Complementary Cumulative
Distribution Function (CCDF), Probability Density Function (PDF), Spectrum
Efficiency, and Outage probability are analyzed. To discuss the system
performance, various receive diversity schemes such as Selection Combining
(SC), Maximal Ratio Combining (MRC) and Equal Gain Combining (EGC)
have been considered under different adaptation policies.
In particular, four adaptation policies are considered: Optimal
simultaneous Power and Rate Adaptation (OPRA) policy, Optimal Rate
Adaptation with constant transmit power (ORA) policy, Channel Inversion
with Fixed Rate (CIFR) policy and Truncated Channel Inversion with Fixed
vii
Rate (TIFR) policy. Moreover, performance analysis of Signal-to-Interference
Ratio (SIR) operating over Rayleigh fading channels experiencing an arbitrary
number of multiple, Rayleigh co-channel interferers is also presented.
Closed-form expressions are derived for performance measures like
ergodic capacity, outage probability, spectrum efficiency versus Signal to
Noise plus Interference Ratio (SNIR). Also, the CCDF, and the PDF of
capacity are derived and plotted.
• Numerical results are provided with plots comprising parametric
measures explaining the system performance in detail.
• Also, graphical results show a comparison between the diversity
schemes and the adaptation policies considered.
• Spectrum efficiency improves with an increase in diversity order and
an increase in the average SNIR.
For the Co-channel interference case, the highlights of this research work are as
follows:
i. Comparing the cases of SC, MRC, and EGC diversity schemes,
capacity improvement shown by OPRA policy is relatively higher as
compared to the other policies.
ii. CIFR policy shows the least spectrum efficiency as compared to the
other policies.
viii
iii. MRC diversity scheme provides the highest spectrum efficiency when
compared to EGC and SC diversity schemes.
iv. SC diversity scheme provides least spectrum efficiency when
compared to MRC and EGC diversity schemes.
For the Adjacent channel interference case, the highlights of this research work
are as follows:
i. Spectrum efficiency improves with increase in Gain of the amplifier
(G), and diversity order (M), with a corresponding increase in average
Signal to Noise Ratio.
ii. Also, with SC diversity scheme, capacity shows considerable
improvement when compared to the system without diversity.
iii. Spectrum efficiency improvement obtained by OPRA policy is higher
when compared to the other policies.
The analytical closed-form expressions derived are validated by
comparing the simulation results with the system whose specifications are
given by the WiMAX IEEE 802.16 standard. The simulation result shows that
analytical expressions yield spectrum efficiency in the range given by the
WiMAX standard, thus validating the results of this research work.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/6870">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/6870</a></td></tr>
